{"key":"processedPost-11890171","value":{"id":11890171,"first":11889811,"last":24894539,"when":1264351959,"utime":"01/24/10 06:52 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>Kysmoker said:</strong><br />Ive heard the bag actually shrinks with the substrate, that way theres no exposed myc on the sides. Ive also heard aluminum foil does the same job fairly well.</blockquote><br />The problem with foil is it doesn't adhere to the substrate as it shrinks the way plastic does.&nbsp; In addition, the foil reflects light down into the crack, providing the best possible environment for side pinning.&nbsp; Don't use foil.<br />If you really want to ENCOURAGE side pinning, use foil.&nbsp; That's how I got this jar to pin so well invitro around the very edges.&nbsp; The jar was wrapped with foil and then exposed to fruiting conditions.&nbsp; I realize this is a monotub thread, but the concept is the same.<br />RR<br /><a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/06-03/747203393-Redboy_invitro_002a.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/06-03/747203393-thumb_Redboy_invitro_002a.jpg\"></a>","title":"Re: Holes in a monotub"}}